515
00:18:22,901 --> 00:18:25,300
Emergency!

516
00:18:25,301 --> 00:18:26,600
- Hurry up!
-  Are you okay?

517
00:18:26,601 --> 00:18:27,970
Hurry up!

518
00:18:27,971 --> 00:18:30,041
- Hurry up?
-  Yes, hurry up!

519
00:18:30,371 --> 00:18:32,010
You told me not to pick random apples.

520
00:18:32,011 --> 00:18:33,281
Now, you picked all the small ones.

521
00:18:34,381 --> 00:18:36,280
(The taster is in a rush.)

522
00:18:36,281 --> 00:18:38,581
- Okay.
-  You picked so many.

523
00:18:39,321 --> 00:18:40,380
All right.

524
00:18:40,381 --> 00:18:41,391
(Working hard until the end)

525
00:18:43,891 --> 00:18:46,120
Everyone, you have five seconds!

526
00:18:46,121 --> 00:18:47,631
Five, four,

527
00:18:48,031 --> 00:18:50,531
three, two, one!

528
00:18:50,631 --> 00:18:52,800
The end!

529
00:18:52,801 --> 00:18:54,730
- It's over, guys. Stop.
-  Stop!

530
00:18:54,731 --> 00:18:56,601
- It's over!
-  All right.

531
00:18:56,701 --> 00:18:58,041
Guys.

532
00:18:58,141 --> 00:18:59,871
It'll take too long to count them one at a time.

533
00:19:00,141 --> 00:19:02,940
- The owner, Ju Eun's mom, - Yes.

534
00:19:02,941 --> 00:19:04,610
will judge the winner.

535
00:19:04,611 --> 00:19:05,980
Go and get your mom.

536
00:19:05,981 --> 00:19:07,181
Here she comes.

537
00:19:07,281 --> 00:19:09,250
Her mom is here.

538
00:19:09,251 --> 00:19:10,750
Pick ours!

539
00:19:10,751 --> 00:19:12,650
We worked hard and picked these apples.

540
00:19:12,651 --> 00:19:15,451
- Right.
-  There were two teams.

541
00:19:15,651 --> 00:19:19,160
Now, you will look at them. And decide who the winner is.

542
00:19:19,161 --> 00:19:21,490
- Which team picked more apples?
-  Okay.

543
00:19:21,491 --> 00:19:22,791
- Do you understand?
-  Yes.

544
00:19:23,361 --> 00:19:27,100
It doesn't count if there are too many scratches.

545
00:19:27,101 --> 00:19:28,270
- Too many what?
-  Scratches.

546
00:19:28,271 --> 00:19:29,330
- Yes.
-  Like scars.

547
00:19:29,331 --> 00:19:31,070
- Yes.
-  That's great.

548
00:19:31,071 --> 00:19:33,140
- This one looks okay.
-  This one has a scratch.

549
00:19:33,141 --> 00:19:34,141
- Well...
-  No.

550
00:19:34,142 --> 00:19:35,740
This one's fine because it's always been there.

551
00:19:35,741 --> 00:19:37,310
- It's always been there.
-  It was already there.

552
00:19:37,311 --> 00:19:38,580
And everyone has a scar.

553
00:19:38,581 --> 00:19:40,140
You grow up pretty only if you have scars.

554
00:19:40,141 --> 00:19:41,450
Check this one.

555
00:19:41,451 --> 00:19:42,611
I have many scratches.

556
00:19:43,251 --> 00:19:45,181
- First off...
-  First off,

557
00:19:45,281 --> 00:19:47,751
how does it look at a glance?

558
00:19:48,951 --> 00:19:50,520
- This is so hard.
-  This one....

559
00:19:50,521 --> 00:19:52,461
- Sorry? It's hard?
-  Yes.

560
00:19:52,561 --> 00:19:55,061
If you had to give them to a customer...

561
00:19:55,161 --> 00:19:56,430
If you had to sell them,

562
00:19:56,431 --> 00:19:57,761
which one would you sell?

563
00:19:58,031 --> 00:19:59,160
Please!

564
00:19:59,161 --> 00:20:02,870
- These ones look better.
-  These ones?

565
00:20:02,871 --> 00:20:03,871
Yes.

566
00:20:05,271 --> 00:20:07,641
(Team Potato wins.)

567
00:20:08,341 --> 00:20:10,041
(Yes!)

568
00:20:10,611 --> 00:20:12,580
(Team Tae Ri loses.)

569
00:20:12,581 --> 00:20:13,581
These ones are fine too.

570
00:20:13,582 --> 00:20:16,610
- These aren't that bad.
-  But...

571
00:20:16,611 --> 00:20:19,120
- But...
-  But those ones are a bit better.

572
00:20:19,121 --> 00:20:21,420
- Just a bit. We won by a hair.
-  Yes.

573
00:20:21,421 --> 00:20:23,291
- These are better products?
-  Yes.

574
00:20:23,451 --> 00:20:24,890
You should have examined them before you picked them.

575
00:20:24,891 --> 00:20:26,860
We actually had...

576
00:20:26,861 --> 00:20:28,130
- Kyung Mo...
-  Kyung Mo.

577
00:20:28,131 --> 00:20:30,360
Kyung Mo stopped us from picking poor ones.

578
00:20:30,361 --> 00:20:32,000
- Did you stop them?
-  Yes.

579
00:20:32,001 --> 00:20:33,230
Oh, really?

580
00:20:33,231 --> 00:20:34,730
- And he was like, - We followed his instructions.

581
00:20:34,731 --> 00:20:36,300
"Come over here," and I came,

582
00:20:36,301 --> 00:20:37,601
and he said, "Pick this one."

583
00:20:38,101 --> 00:20:39,370
All I did was pick them.

584
00:20:39,371 --> 00:20:40,701
Did you really?

585
00:20:41,711 --> 00:20:43,870
(A nine-year-old's strict apple philosophy)

586
00:20:43,871 --> 00:20:44,880
How does it look?

587
00:20:44,881 --> 00:20:46,080
- Good.
-  Good?

588
00:20:46,081 --> 00:20:48,150
(Today's MVP, Kyung Mo)

589
00:20:48,151 --> 00:20:50,920
All right, then. How does it feel to win?

590
00:20:50,921 --> 00:20:52,380
How do you feel, Kyung Mo?

591
00:20:52,381 --> 00:20:53,881
Product value is more important.

592
00:20:54,451 --> 00:20:55,591
Product value is more important?

593
00:20:55,851 --> 00:20:58,320
I'm sorry, but do you own this orchard?

594
00:20:58,321 --> 00:21:00,091
Everything he says is impressive.

595
00:21:00,791 --> 00:21:02,590
- Yes.
-  Product value is important.

596
00:21:02,591 --> 00:21:04,260
- Great work, everyone.
-  Let's give it up.

597
00:21:04,261 --> 00:21:05,560
- You picked the right ones.
-  Yes.

598
00:21:05,561 --> 00:21:08,331
Let's go and eat, kids.

599
00:21:10,631 --> 00:21:11,971
Did you apologize?

600
00:21:12,171 --> 00:21:14,510
No? Tell him to apologize.

601
00:21:14,511 --> 00:21:15,940
Hey.

602
00:21:15,941 --> 00:21:18,840
- Do Hyun, you have to apologize.
-  I did.

603
00:21:18,841 --> 00:21:19,980
- No, you didn't!
-  He said you didn't.

604
00:21:19,981 --> 00:21:22,010
- But I did.
-  But he said you didn't.

605
00:21:22,011 --> 00:21:23,011
I'm sorry.

606
00:21:25,981 --> 00:21:26,981
What happened?

607
00:21:27,481 --> 00:21:28,921
- I'll explain.
-  Okay.

608
00:21:29,151 --> 00:21:33,790
Do Hyun held Hyo Min's hand,

609
00:21:33,791 --> 00:21:35,530
but there was snot, apparently.

610
00:21:35,531 --> 00:21:37,860
So, Hyo Min has been feeling bad about it.

611
00:21:37,861 --> 00:21:39,530
But he never got his apology.

612
00:21:39,531 --> 00:21:42,571
He wants to say sorry now, but he won't accept it.

613
00:21:42,671 --> 00:21:43,701
What should we do?

614
00:21:43,801 --> 00:21:45,540
- What do we tell them?
-  Hyo Min,

615
00:21:45,541 --> 00:21:46,871
can I tell you something?

616
00:21:47,271 --> 00:21:50,110
Ms. Kim and I also argued a lot.

617
00:21:50,111 --> 00:21:51,180
We fight all the time.

618
00:21:51,181 --> 00:21:52,911
We were actually in a fight.

619
00:21:53,011 --> 00:21:54,180
- We're serious.
-  Seriously.

620
00:21:54,181 --> 00:21:55,310
We'll show you what we did.

621
00:21:55,311 --> 00:21:56,650
(They tell the kids their own story.)

622
00:21:56,651 --> 00:21:59,621
Look. Here's how we made up, Hyo Min.

623
00:21:59,721 --> 00:22:00,751
Here's how we made up.

624
00:22:00,851 --> 00:22:02,190
In 1, 2, 3.

625
00:22:02,191 --> 00:22:04,890
- I'm sorry, friend.
-  I'm sorry, friend.

626
00:22:04,891 --> 00:22:07,190
- Thank you, and I love you.
-  Thank you, and I love you.

627
00:22:07,191 --> 00:22:09,591
- Yuck!
-  What?

628
00:22:11,361 --> 00:22:12,401
- What do you think?
-  That's how we made up.

629
00:22:13,601 --> 00:22:15,631
- Hyo Min, I'm sorry.
-  Whatever.

630
00:22:16,071 --> 00:22:17,470
- Do it together.
-  Why don't we give it a try?

631
00:22:17,471 --> 00:22:18,740
- Let's hold hands and try it.
-  Yes.

632
00:22:18,741 --> 00:22:19,771
Hyo Min.

633
00:22:20,841 --> 00:22:21,841
Come on, Hyo Min.

634
00:22:21,842 --> 00:22:23,171
(Hyo Min gets sulky and leaves.)

635
00:22:23,271 --> 00:22:25,210
But he said sorry, right?

636
00:22:25,211 --> 00:22:27,811
Ju Eun, what should we do to help them make up?

637
00:22:30,281 --> 00:22:31,281
No!

638
00:22:31,282 --> 00:22:33,551
(Ju Eun comforts him without a word.)

639
00:22:33,651 --> 00:22:36,420
- Do Hyun, are you all right?
-  Yes.

640
00:22:36,421 --> 00:22:38,560
This is part of growing.

641
00:22:38,561 --> 00:22:39,561
Okay.

642
00:22:40,121 --> 00:22:41,761
I also got into a lot of fights in elementary school.

643
00:22:42,361 --> 00:22:43,530
And I cried a lot.

644
00:22:43,531 --> 00:22:46,801
But this will teach you...

645
00:22:46,901 --> 00:22:48,801
how to make up with friends.

646
00:22:49,531 --> 00:22:50,531
- Mr. Choi.
-  Yes?

647
00:22:50,532 --> 00:22:51,900
You had Eclipse mints, didn't you?

648
00:22:51,901 --> 00:22:52,940
Yes, how did you know?

649
00:22:52,941 --> 00:22:53,970
I could smell it.

650
00:22:53,971 --> 00:22:55,471
- You even know about Eclipse?
-  Yes.

651
00:22:56,371 --> 00:22:57,410
Do you want one?

652
00:22:57,411 --> 00:22:58,540
- No, it's okay.
-  No?

653
00:22:58,541 --> 00:22:59,780
I got this one!

654
00:22:59,781 --> 00:23:00,981
Really?

655
00:23:01,081 --> 00:23:03,781
- I'll pick an apple too.
-  I picked a really pretty one.

656
00:23:05,981 --> 00:23:10,091
(He picks an apple and wipes it cleanly.)

657
00:23:11,421 --> 00:23:13,590
Wouldn't it be better to give this to Hyo Min?

658
00:23:13,591 --> 00:23:15,030
Yes, give him this.

659
00:23:15,031 --> 00:23:16,960
- Say, "Accept my apology." - Go to him.

660
00:23:16,961 --> 00:23:18,630
(He got an apple to apologize.)

661
00:23:18,631 --> 00:23:20,000
Hyo Min.

662
00:23:20,001 --> 00:23:22,271
- Will you accept my apology?
-  "Accept my apology."

663
00:23:23,931 --> 00:23:25,640
I got a good one.

664
00:23:25,641 --> 00:23:26,771
Isn't it pretty?

665
00:23:27,071 --> 00:23:28,141
Hyo Min looks...

666
00:23:29,511 --> 00:23:31,311
- Do you accept it?
-  Will you accept my apology?

667
00:23:32,081 --> 00:23:34,210
You can keep this, and I'll keep this one.

668
00:23:34,211 --> 00:23:35,410
Okay, here you go.

669
00:23:35,411 --> 00:23:36,850
(They exchange apples and make up.)

670
00:23:36,851 --> 00:23:38,451
He finally accepted my apology.

671
00:23:38,621 --> 00:23:40,180
Are you all right?

672
00:23:40,181 --> 00:23:42,821
(And the kids made peace.)

673
00:23:42,851 --> 00:23:46,891
When Hyo Min and Do Hyun had a fight,

674
00:23:47,461 --> 00:23:50,591
I thought, "It happens to elementary school boys."

675
00:23:50,831 --> 00:23:52,101
I did the same.

676
00:23:52,561 --> 00:23:53,901
It's natural for them.

677
00:23:54,731 --> 00:23:57,071
But I believe you need to make things clear...

678
00:23:57,271 --> 00:23:59,671
before you make up.

679
00:24:00,501 --> 00:24:03,941
Do Hyun gave Hyo Min an apple, right?

680
00:24:04,741 --> 00:24:06,141
That was so mature.

681
00:24:06,941 --> 00:24:10,211
It made me reflect on myself.

682
00:24:10,751 --> 00:24:13,851
I learn a lot from them.

683
00:24:13,951 --> 00:24:16,591
Watching these elementary school kids.

684
00:24:18,191 --> 00:24:19,191
Yes.

685
00:24:20,191 --> 00:24:21,490
Let's go have snacks!

686
00:24:21,491 --> 00:24:22,890
- Yes!
-  Let's go.

687
00:24:22,891 --> 00:24:23,960
Come on. No way!

688
00:24:23,961 --> 00:24:25,560
- Jjajangmyeon?
-  It's jjajangmyeon.

689
00:24:25,561 --> 00:24:26,760
Are those fried dumplings?

690
00:24:26,761 --> 00:24:28,200
It's jjajangmyeon!

691
00:24:28,201 --> 00:24:29,870
Should we start eating, guys?

692
00:24:29,871 --> 00:24:32,041
- Yes!
-  Thank you for the food!

693
00:24:33,571 --> 00:24:34,740
You can't wait to eat it, can you?

694
00:24:34,741 --> 00:24:36,771
(Let's mix it.)

695
00:24:36,941 --> 00:24:38,540
All done.

696
00:24:38,541 --> 00:24:40,341
I can't remember the last time I had jjajangmyeon.

697
00:24:40,611 --> 00:24:42,251
This is good jjajangmyeon.

698
00:24:42,511 --> 00:24:44,481
(Slurping)

699
00:24:44,581 --> 00:24:46,151
Eat slowly, okay?

700
00:24:46,521 --> 00:24:47,521
It's delicious.

701
00:24:47,522 --> 00:24:49,321
(Sucking)

702
00:24:50,351 --> 00:24:53,261
(The teachers enjoy it as well.)

703
00:24:54,161 --> 00:24:55,990
(Slurping)

704
00:24:55,991 --> 00:24:57,760
It tastes better after working hard, doesn't it?

705
00:24:57,761 --> 00:25:00,000
(It tastes way better after hard work.)

706
00:25:00,001 --> 00:25:01,800
We can bring phones and computers.

707
00:25:01,801 --> 00:25:03,771
(Enjoying)

708
00:25:04,941 --> 00:25:07,440
You should come over to my house.

709
00:25:07,441 --> 00:25:09,741
- Can I?
-  Yes. Today!

710
00:25:10,441 --> 00:25:12,681
Can I come over today? What will you do for me?

711
00:25:13,281 --> 00:25:14,381
- At my house?
-  Yes.

712
00:25:14,881 --> 00:25:16,081
I'll give you ten dollars.

713
00:25:18,221 --> 00:25:21,051
(I'm Kim Kyung Mo, a generous 9-year-old.)

714
00:25:21,551 --> 00:25:23,321
I'll come for free. Why would I accept that?

715
00:25:27,421 --> 00:25:29,691
(Reading the room)

716
00:25:30,191 --> 00:25:32,101
Why am I the only one who's left-handed?

717
00:25:32,301 --> 00:25:34,061
- What?
-  It means you're special.

718
00:25:34,701 --> 00:25:36,631
I've always wanted to be left-handed.

719
00:25:36,901 --> 00:25:37,971
Really?

720
00:25:38,171 --> 00:25:39,570
(He tries using his left hand.)

721
00:25:39,571 --> 00:25:42,871
(And he tries using his right hand.)

722
00:25:43,641 --> 00:25:44,681
- Eat with your left hand.
-  Okay.

723
00:25:45,711 --> 00:25:46,810
- Okay?
-  Okay.

724
00:25:46,811 --> 00:25:48,251
You don't have to force yourself to use your right hand.

725
00:25:48,281 --> 00:25:49,711
You can just eat with your left hand.

726
00:25:49,781 --> 00:25:51,010
- Is he left-handed?
-  Yes.

727
00:25:51,011 --> 00:25:52,650
- Left-handed...
-  He was using his right hand...

728
00:25:52,651 --> 00:25:53,950
on purpose because everyone else was using their right hands.

729
00:25:53,951 --> 00:25:56,050
- Many geniuses are left-handed.
-  You're a genius.

730
00:25:56,051 --> 00:25:58,061
Left-handed baseball pitchers are rare.

731
00:25:58,191 --> 00:25:59,760
- You're rare. You know that.
-  Yes.

732
00:25:59,761 --> 00:26:00,761
Right?

733
00:26:02,831 --> 00:26:06,261
(He comfortably uses his left hand, thanks to them.)

734
00:26:08,001 --> 00:26:10,400
Teacher, this is recording.

735
00:26:10,401 --> 00:26:11,671
Yes, I'm recording it.

736
00:26:11,971 --> 00:26:13,670
(Mr. CO brought a recorder.)

737
00:26:13,671 --> 00:26:14,741
I'll show you.

738
00:26:15,911 --> 00:26:18,241
- I want to try it.
-  Yes, listen to it.

739
00:26:20,311 --> 00:26:22,381
- Do you hear it?
-  Yes.

740
00:26:25,251 --> 00:26:26,850
Do you want to record yourself eating jjajangmyeon?

741
00:26:26,851 --> 00:26:28,450
(He tries ASMR while eating jjajangmyeon.)

742
00:26:28,451 --> 00:26:31,151
(So cute)

743
00:26:37,961 --> 00:26:39,800
That's so interesting!

744
00:26:39,801 --> 00:26:41,061
Right?

745
00:26:41,271 --> 00:26:42,500
I want to try it too!

746
00:26:42,501 --> 00:26:44,201
Bamboo helicopter!

747
00:26:44,301 --> 00:26:45,901
I want to try it too!

748
00:26:45,971 --> 00:26:48,140
Guys, isn't this so fun?

749
00:26:48,141 --> 00:26:49,541
- I hear it.
-  Right?

750
00:26:49,641 --> 00:26:50,910
- What?
-  Hi.

751
00:26:50,911 --> 00:26:54,011
I'm their music teacher and music director.

752
00:26:54,611 --> 00:26:58,481
The music I make only exists for the kids.

753
00:26:58,821 --> 00:27:01,391
This is a kids' play, so I feel like...

754
00:27:01,521 --> 00:27:03,020
they'll find it fun...

755
00:27:03,021 --> 00:27:05,290
only if they can tell...

756
00:27:05,291 --> 00:27:08,091
that they did it once it's finished.

757
00:27:08,161 --> 00:27:10,490
We're going to make songs for our play...

758
00:27:10,491 --> 00:27:12,761
with the sounds that you make.

759
00:27:13,261 --> 00:27:14,700
Yes, I hear it.

760
00:27:14,701 --> 00:27:15,931
(Squeak)

761
00:27:17,801 --> 00:27:19,740
That's great. Well done.

762
00:27:19,741 --> 00:27:21,341
Awesome. Just a little more.

763
00:27:21,911 --> 00:27:23,370
That sounds so pretty.

764
00:27:23,371 --> 00:27:24,371
(He'll use their sounds to make music and sound effects.)

765
00:27:24,372 --> 00:27:26,511
One, two, three, four, stomp.

766
00:27:27,811 --> 00:27:29,910
I thought I could replace the drum sound...

767
00:27:29,911 --> 00:27:31,581
with their stomps or claps.

768
00:27:33,251 --> 00:27:35,690
(The Witch's laughter)

769
00:27:35,691 --> 00:27:36,691
That was an actual witch.

770
00:27:39,421 --> 00:27:40,990
Various animal sounds.

771
00:27:40,991 --> 00:27:43,191
(Various animal sounds)

772
00:27:46,701 --> 00:27:50,200
I also recorded sound effects that kids might find fun.

773
00:27:50,201 --> 00:27:51,541
(They make various sound effects together.)

774
00:27:52,601 --> 00:27:54,140
Here goes Potato Teacher.

775
00:27:54,141 --> 00:27:55,541
(Potato Teacher's horn sound)

776
00:27:56,011 --> 00:27:59,040
(Blowing an airhorn)

777
00:27:59,041 --> 00:28:00,711
(Stopping)

778
00:28:01,981 --> 00:28:03,081
Did his voice crack?

779
00:28:04,611 --> 00:28:06,780
- His voice cracked at the end.
-  Mr. Choi.

780
00:28:06,781 --> 00:28:08,150
You just had a reality check, didn't you?

781
00:28:08,151 --> 00:28:09,320
- No, I didn't.
-  A reality check?

782
00:28:09,321 --> 00:28:10,750
You sounded so embarrassed.

783
00:28:10,751 --> 00:28:12,160
- Oh, my gosh.
-  I didn't.

784
00:28:12,161 --> 00:28:13,261
(On the ground)

785
00:28:13,721 --> 00:28:15,160
Poor him.

786
00:28:15,161 --> 00:28:17,391
- His face turned red.
-  No, it didn't.

787
00:28:18,501 --> 00:28:21,100
(A red potato)

788
00:28:21,101 --> 00:28:25,200
All these sounds are memories to the children...

789
00:28:25,201 --> 00:28:26,671
and the teachers who worked on them.

790
00:28:26,871 --> 00:28:29,070
I hope it's like...

791
00:28:29,071 --> 00:28:32,410
going through a photo album after a long time.

792
00:28:32,411 --> 00:28:33,611
That's what I want it to be like.

793
00:28:33,911 --> 00:28:35,080
That was great, though.

794
00:28:35,081 --> 00:28:37,351
All done, everyone.

795
00:28:37,581 --> 00:28:38,780
Great work.

796
00:28:38,781 --> 00:28:41,151
(The sounds of the acting class are coming soon.)

797
00:28:41,521 --> 00:28:46,060
Guys, we have a new teacher, right?

798
00:28:46,061 --> 00:28:49,430
I'd like to show Mr. CO...

799
00:28:49,431 --> 00:28:52,130
what we've been working on.

800
00:28:52,131 --> 00:28:53,830
Remember the Wicked Witch of the West's scene?

801
00:28:53,831 --> 00:28:55,501
The one we practiced.

802
00:28:56,471 --> 00:28:58,771
(They practiced the Wicked Witch of the West's scene two days ago.)

803
00:28:59,871 --> 00:29:02,171
(However,)

804
00:29:03,241 --> 00:29:06,911
(the kids couldn't memorize all the lines.)

805
00:29:08,251 --> 00:29:12,051
(So, they gave them homework of memorizing the script.)

806
00:29:12,551 --> 00:29:14,550
We can go from Page 9 to Page 12...

807
00:29:14,551 --> 00:29:16,050
without looking at the script.

808
00:29:16,051 --> 00:29:17,620
- Seriously?
-  Really?

809
00:29:17,621 --> 00:29:19,060
- Really!
-  Everyone can?

810
00:29:19,061 --> 00:29:21,760
We even made a group chatroom and practiced.

811
00:29:21,761 --> 00:29:22,930
- Really?
-  Really?

812
00:29:22,931 --> 00:29:26,730
- We should check it out, then.
-  We should.

813
00:29:26,731 --> 00:29:28,131
Can you show us?

814
00:29:28,271 --> 00:29:30,570
- Yes!
-  All right, then.

815
00:29:30,571 --> 00:29:34,040
Eun Soo isn't here at the moment,

816
00:29:34,041 --> 00:29:35,470
so we need someone to play Dorothy today.

817
00:29:35,471 --> 00:29:37,471
- Who will it be?
-  Who will it be?

818
00:29:37,671 --> 00:29:39,080
I'm Dorothy.

819
00:29:39,081 --> 00:29:40,740
- Okay, thank you in advance.
-  You're Dorothy for the day.

820
00:29:40,741 --> 00:29:42,381
Yes, I'm Dorothy for the day.

821
00:29:43,081 --> 00:29:45,721
Let's start...

822
00:29:46,381 --> 00:29:48,121
the performance.

823
00:29:48,451 --> 00:29:50,191
Let's start, then.

824
00:29:50,491 --> 00:29:54,060
It's set in a dark forest, and the curtain opens.

825
00:29:54,061 --> 00:29:57,931
- Dorothy and her friends appear.
-  Let's go to the center.

826
00:29:58,201 --> 00:30:00,931
The Wicked Witch still has her face covered.

827
00:30:01,701 --> 00:30:03,170
Sniff.

828
00:30:03,171 --> 00:30:05,171
I smell fire.

829
00:30:05,601 --> 00:30:06,640
Scarecrow.

830
00:30:06,641 --> 00:30:09,670
What? Fire? It's going to burn all my straws!

831
00:30:09,671 --> 00:30:11,711
- No!
-  No!

832
00:30:12,381 --> 00:30:13,381
Dorothy!

833
00:30:13,381 --> 00:30:14,381
(Shivering)

834
00:30:14,481 --> 00:30:16,250
We meet at last.

835
00:30:16,251 --> 00:30:20,081
I knew you would go to meet the Wizard of Oz.

836
00:30:20,421 --> 00:30:22,051
(Seeing Ju Eun the Witch for the first time)

837
00:30:22,191 --> 00:30:24,791
But these are regular shoes.

838
00:30:25,321 --> 00:30:28,560
With those shoes, I'll be the strongest in the universe,

839
00:30:28,561 --> 00:30:29,590
She's good.

840
00:30:29,591 --> 00:30:32,731
and I can take the Emerald Castle and Oz!

841
00:30:33,101 --> 00:30:35,671
Then, I cannot give you these shoes.

842
00:30:36,101 --> 00:30:38,030
The Witch shoots fire.

843
00:30:38,031 --> 00:30:39,670
- Props.
-  Here.

844
00:30:39,671 --> 00:30:41,040
- Fire!
-  Fire!

845
00:30:41,041 --> 00:30:43,071
- Fire!
-  Fire!

846
00:30:43,641 --> 00:30:45,481
- Take me away.
-  I'll take you.

847
00:30:45,611 --> 00:30:47,480
No!

848
00:30:47,481 --> 00:30:49,481
- She's taking me!
-  Dorothy!

849
00:30:50,781 --> 00:30:51,950
(He quickly sets up the lake for the next scene.)

850
00:30:51,951 --> 00:30:54,620
The curtain closes.

851
00:30:54,621 --> 00:30:58,320
- Great.
-  Now, the curtain opens.

852
00:30:58,321 --> 00:31:00,420
First, the Witch and Dorothy.

853
00:31:00,421 --> 00:31:01,660
They're having a quarrel.

854
00:31:01,661 --> 00:31:04,030
- No!
-  Her friends arrived later.

855
00:31:04,031 --> 00:31:06,101
(Her friends are on the other side of the lake.)

856
00:31:06,231 --> 00:31:08,370
Oh, no, Dorothy.

857
00:31:08,371 --> 00:31:11,641
She's on the other side of the lake.

858
00:31:12,001 --> 00:31:15,070
How do we get rid of the lake... No, the witch.

859
00:31:15,071 --> 00:31:16,370
And cross the lake...

860
00:31:16,371 --> 00:31:18,241
- "Bring Dorothy back." - Bring Dorothy back?

861
00:31:18,441 --> 00:31:19,511
So cute.

862
00:31:20,541 --> 00:31:22,051
Let's save her.

863
00:31:22,551 --> 00:31:24,080
But the Wicked Witch of the West is too powerful.

864
00:31:24,081 --> 00:31:26,081
We won't stand a chance, even if we work together.

865
00:31:26,551 --> 00:31:28,490
But the Wicked Witch of the West is made of fire,

866
00:31:28,491 --> 00:31:30,391
so she'll disappear if she touches water.

867
00:31:30,551 --> 00:31:31,560
(They flawlessly say the lines back and forth.)

868
00:31:31,561 --> 00:31:33,760
But how do we cross the lake?

869
00:31:33,761 --> 00:31:36,630
I have my strong legs,

870
00:31:36,631 --> 00:31:40,331
- so I'll go and save Dorothy.
-  So I'll...

871
00:31:41,161 --> 00:31:42,800
The lion crosses, guys!

872
00:31:42,801 --> 00:31:44,871
(He jumps over the lake with his strong legs.)

873
00:31:45,071 --> 00:31:47,370
- Put her in the lake.
-  He put her in the lake.

874
00:31:47,371 --> 00:31:50,240
No, I can't believe you figured out my weakness.

875
00:31:50,241 --> 00:31:51,610
Water is my weakness.

876
00:31:51,611 --> 00:31:53,940
I had so many wicked plans!

877
00:31:53,941 --> 00:31:55,911
Unfortunately, I must go.

878
00:31:56,111 --> 00:31:59,220
Yes! The Witch exits.

879
00:31:59,221 --> 00:32:00,680
In 1, 2, 3.

880
00:32:00,681 --> 00:32:03,890
- Yes, the Lion has done it!
-  Yes, the Lion has done it!

881
00:32:03,891 --> 00:32:06,491
- Thank you, Lion!
-  Thank you, Lion!

882
00:32:06,921 --> 00:32:09,891
(Perfect to the final line)

883
00:32:10,161 --> 00:32:12,100
Three stamps!

884
00:32:12,101 --> 00:32:14,631
(Clapping)

885
00:32:15,501 --> 00:32:17,130
- You guys are good.
-  Well done.

886
00:32:17,131 --> 00:32:19,401
- Hyo Min, you were so good.
-  That was fantastic.

887
00:32:20,341 --> 00:32:22,511
I've never seen them work together as one.

888
00:32:22,971 --> 00:32:25,081
We told them that they should memorize the lines.

889
00:32:25,181 --> 00:32:27,740
But to be honest, I never thought it was possible.

890
00:32:27,741 --> 00:32:30,711
I thought that they wouldn't be able to do it since they were kids.

891
00:32:30,881 --> 00:32:33,821
But that made me realize it could actually work.

892
00:32:34,181 --> 00:32:35,521
They just memorized the whole script.

893
00:32:35,621 --> 00:32:37,450
We had so little time.

894
00:32:37,451 --> 00:32:41,791
I felt hopeful that we might actually pull it off.

895
00:32:43,561 --> 00:32:45,230
Kids,

896
00:32:45,231 --> 00:32:48,100
when Mr. CO KUN leaves today,

897
00:32:48,101 --> 00:32:49,870
we won't be able to see him for a few days.

898
00:32:49,871 --> 00:32:51,940
- I'll see you on TV.
-  I'll be back soon.

899
00:32:51,941 --> 00:32:52,941
Great job today.

900
00:32:52,942 --> 00:32:54,640
- Good work, everyone!
-  Thank you for your hard work.

901
00:32:54,641 --> 00:32:55,710
- Thanks.
-  Bye.

902
00:32:55,711 --> 00:32:57,071
- Yes!
-  Bye-bye.

903
00:32:57,271 --> 00:32:58,380
- Bye, Mr. CO.
-  Thanks, guys.

904
00:32:58,381 --> 00:33:00,511
It wasn't the end.

905
00:33:00,811 --> 00:33:03,250
Mr. CO will definitely...

906
00:33:03,251 --> 00:33:05,681
come back to see them before the rehearsal.

907
00:33:06,481 --> 00:33:08,550
I'll take a photo of you too.

908
00:33:08,551 --> 00:33:09,821
Will you?

909
00:33:11,491 --> 00:33:13,321
(Click)

910
00:33:14,821 --> 00:33:16,130
I'll be back soon.

911
00:33:16,131 --> 00:33:20,061
(Mr. CO will return with his songs.)

912
00:33:24,771 --> 00:33:29,371
(A new week begins after Mr. CO left.)

913
00:33:31,811 --> 00:33:33,710
(Yongheung Elementary School Mini Autumn Field Day)

914
00:33:33,711 --> 00:33:36,881
(The school bus arrives.)

915
00:33:40,921 --> 00:33:43,851
(Eun Soo from acting class shows up.)

916
00:33:46,821 --> 00:33:49,861
(Hyo Min also shows up with messy hair.)

917
00:33:50,761 --> 00:33:53,560
(It's a special day!)

918
00:33:53,561 --> 00:33:58,571
(Yongheung Elementary School Mini Autumn Field Day)

919
00:34:00,471 --> 00:34:03,171
(Meanwhile, in the Mushroom House)

920
00:34:04,441 --> 00:34:07,741
(Opening)

921
00:34:09,211 --> 00:34:12,651
(Kangnam woke up early at 7:50am.)

922
00:34:17,221 --> 00:34:20,621
(Unknown ingredients)

923
00:34:22,191 --> 00:34:24,690
(And there's a letter.)

924
00:34:24,691 --> 00:34:26,400
(Hi, Ms. Kim. It's Ahn Sung Jae.)

925
00:34:26,401 --> 00:34:28,230
(Thank you for giving me the chance to cook delicious food...)

926
00:34:28,231 --> 00:34:30,070
(for the children of Yongheung Elementary School.)

927
00:34:30,071 --> 00:34:32,040
(I sent you the necessary ingredients beforehand.)

928
00:34:32,041 --> 00:34:34,000
(I'll see you soon. From Ahn Sung Jae.)

929
00:34:34,001 --> 00:34:36,941
(From Ahn Sung Jae?)

930
00:34:38,641 --> 00:34:40,181
Look at all those apples.

931
00:34:41,541 --> 00:34:42,711
Mungyeong apples.

932
00:34:45,381 --> 00:34:47,981
(There's a guest early in the morning.)

933
00:34:49,221 --> 00:34:51,721
(Anybody here?)

934
00:34:52,161 --> 00:34:53,161
Excuse me?

935
00:34:53,861 --> 00:34:54,861
Ms. Kim?

936
00:34:55,991 --> 00:34:58,401
Hi, I'm chef Ahn Sung Jae.

937
00:34:58,961 --> 00:35:02,271
It's the school's field day,

938
00:35:02,801 --> 00:35:05,641
and I got the chance to cook for the children.

939
00:35:06,401 --> 00:35:08,610
And the timing was good.

940
00:35:08,611 --> 00:35:10,541
So, I've come here.

941
00:35:16,751 --> 00:35:18,311
(Screaming)

942
00:35:18,521 --> 00:35:19,521
Seriously?

943
00:35:19,522 --> 00:35:22,221
(They hear the bell.)

944
00:35:22,421 --> 00:35:23,421
Seriously?

945
00:35:24,321 --> 00:35:25,691
Did the bell ring?

946
00:35:26,591 --> 00:35:28,060
I'm all over the place.

947
00:35:28,061 --> 00:35:29,231
I didn't even hear it.

948
00:35:30,831 --> 00:35:32,360
(Surprised)

949
00:35:32,361 --> 00:35:33,860
Oh, hi.

950
00:35:33,861 --> 00:35:35,030
(Welcome.)

951
00:35:35,031 --> 00:35:37,231
- Hello.
-  Hello.

952
00:35:37,671 --> 00:35:39,300
- Come on in.
-  It's nice to meet you.

953
00:35:39,301 --> 00:35:40,541
- Nice to meet you.
-  Welcome.

954
00:35:40,871 --> 00:35:41,871
Oh, boy.

955
00:35:41,872 --> 00:35:43,371
- Here.
-  It's a pleasure.

956
00:35:43,971 --> 00:35:45,510
- Hello.
-  It's nice to meet you.

957
00:35:45,511 --> 00:35:46,981
What was it? I didn't see it.

958
00:35:47,511 --> 00:35:49,550
- It's nothing much.
-  The Heart Shiitake Mushroom House?

959
00:35:49,551 --> 00:35:50,551
- Yes.
-  Yes.

960
00:35:50,552 --> 00:35:52,120
- It looks like a mushroom.
-  It's the Mushroom House.

961
00:35:52,121 --> 00:35:54,851
- Oh, the Mushroom House.
-  Yes, come on in.

962
00:35:56,191 --> 00:35:57,421
When are you leaving?

963
00:35:57,821 --> 00:35:59,061
Later today.

964
00:35:59,361 --> 00:36:00,691
- Really?
-  Yes, in the evening.

965
00:36:01,161 --> 00:36:02,431
- You should sleep over.
-  Here?

966
00:36:02,731 --> 00:36:04,330
- Is there a room for me?
-  It's huge.

967
00:36:04,331 --> 00:36:06,060
- We also have a caravan.
-  Really?

968
00:36:06,061 --> 00:36:07,600
- You could even sleep here.
-  Yes.

969
00:36:07,601 --> 00:36:09,231
- And the wooden bench outside.
-  Right.

970
00:36:09,631 --> 00:36:10,830
It's lovely here.

971
00:36:10,831 --> 00:36:13,240
- Should we...
-  What time is it right now?

972
00:36:13,241 --> 00:36:14,970
- What time is it?
-  What's the time?

973
00:36:14,971 --> 00:36:16,770
- It's 9:30am.
-  It's 9:30am?

974
00:36:16,771 --> 00:36:17,940
When does the food need to be ready?

975
00:36:17,941 --> 00:36:19,740
- Noon.
-  Noon?

976
00:36:19,741 --> 00:36:21,280
- Don't you need just 30 minutes?
-  Should we start?

977
00:36:21,281 --> 00:36:22,351
Well,

978
00:36:22,711 --> 00:36:23,980
- Thirty minutes...
-  we can start later.

979
00:36:23,981 --> 00:36:25,680
- Exactly.
-  We'll take a short break.

980
00:36:25,681 --> 00:36:27,651
- Yes, you just got here too.
-  Oh, I see.

981
00:36:27,751 --> 00:36:29,550
- Thanks for the apples.
-  Eat up.

982
00:36:29,551 --> 00:36:31,521
- We picked them ourselves.
-  Yesterday?

983
00:36:32,161 --> 00:36:34,061
- Where was this?
-  Here.

984
00:36:34,321 --> 00:36:36,630
That means it's from the principal.

985
00:36:36,631 --> 00:36:38,391
- The principal?
-  Yes.

986
00:36:38,961 --> 00:36:41,130
- What's it like?
-  It's our welcome food.

987
00:36:41,131 --> 00:36:42,201
What do you think?

988
00:36:42,471 --> 00:36:43,700
It's rich in sweetness.

989
00:36:43,701 --> 00:36:45,741
- Right? It's so sweet.
-  Yes.

990
00:36:46,141 --> 00:36:47,970
He doesn't just say, "Sweet."

991
00:36:47,971 --> 00:36:49,570
- It's rich in sweetness.
-  "Rich in sweetness."

992
00:36:49,571 --> 00:36:51,771
We should talk like that. "Rich in sweetness."

993
00:36:52,041 --> 00:36:53,540
"It's rich in sweetness."

994
00:36:53,541 --> 00:36:54,881
(She learns it right away.)

995
00:36:55,211 --> 00:36:58,150
We have to come up with a nickname for you.

996
00:36:58,151 --> 00:37:00,181
Did you have a nickname growing up?

997
00:37:00,451 --> 00:37:01,521
- Me?
-  Yes.

998
00:37:02,191 --> 00:37:04,191
- Is there an animal you resemble?
-  An animal?

999
00:37:04,391 --> 00:37:05,960
- He's like...
-  You look like a polar bear.

1000
00:37:05,961 --> 00:37:07,661
No, he's kind of like...

1001
00:37:08,221 --> 00:37:10,260
- This type of animal.
-  A raccoon?

1002
00:37:10,261 --> 00:37:11,261
- No.
-  A squirrel?

1003
00:37:11,262 --> 00:37:12,930
- But...
-  It's in Australia.

1004
00:37:12,931 --> 00:37:14,431
many people tell me...

1005
00:37:15,031 --> 00:37:16,530
- that I look like that whale.
-  Whale?

1006
00:37:16,531 --> 00:37:17,700
What kind of whale was it?

1007
00:37:17,701 --> 00:37:18,940
- Orca?
-  Beluga whale?

1008
00:37:18,941 --> 00:37:20,501
- Beluga whale?
-  Oh, a beluga whale!

1009
00:37:20,801 --> 00:37:21,840
Beluga!

1010
00:37:21,841 --> 00:37:23,410
- I see the resemblance.
-  Beluga!

1011
00:37:23,411 --> 00:37:26,080
- The way it smiles.
-  He does! The white whale.

1012
00:37:26,081 --> 00:37:27,710
(He clearly has the face of a beluga whale.)

1013
00:37:27,711 --> 00:37:28,781
He does.

1014
00:37:29,111 --> 00:37:30,710
Should we call him Beluga Teacher?

1015
00:37:30,711 --> 00:37:33,250
Should it be Beluga Teacher or Whale Teacher?

1016
00:37:33,251 --> 00:37:35,050
Whale Teacher sounds good. It's easier.

1017
00:37:35,051 --> 00:37:36,320
- Whale Teacher.
-  Okay.

1018
00:37:36,321 --> 00:37:37,490
- All right.
-  All right.

1019
00:37:37,491 --> 00:37:38,550
Whale Teacher it is.

1020
00:37:38,551 --> 00:37:40,520
- I'll prepare the food soon.
-  Okay.

1021
00:37:40,521 --> 00:37:43,230
Can you tell us what you're making?

1022
00:37:43,231 --> 00:37:46,130
Today, tomato rose pasta...

1023
00:37:46,131 --> 00:37:47,160
- Rose pasta!
-  Yes.

1024
00:37:47,161 --> 00:37:49,530
I wasn't sure what kids would like, so...

1025
00:37:49,531 --> 00:37:52,340
- I bet they'll love it.
-  Rose pasta sounds great.

1026
00:37:52,341 --> 00:37:55,140
All the restaurants are far away from here,

1027
00:37:55,141 --> 00:37:56,771
- so...
-  So, I thought...

1028
00:37:57,071 --> 00:37:59,211
about making Korean food,

1029
00:37:59,741 --> 00:38:01,951
but I felt like they were used to it.

1030
00:38:02,351 --> 00:38:05,151
So, I'm going to use ham to make a type of tangsuyuk.

1031
00:38:05,581 --> 00:38:08,081
It's tangsuyuk, but some kids can't eat flour,

1032
00:38:08,351 --> 00:38:11,220
so I'll use rice flour and starch powder...

1033
00:38:11,221 --> 00:38:13,021
and deep-fry it.

1034
00:38:13,161 --> 00:38:15,060
- And that...
-  Ripe persimmons.

1035
00:38:15,061 --> 00:38:18,061
Ripe or soft persimmons. I'll use that to make the sauce.

1036
00:38:18,361 --> 00:38:19,860
- Oh, that sounds delicious.
-  The sauce.

1037
00:38:19,861 --> 00:38:21,800
- It sounds so good.
-  I'll use that and vinegar...

1038
00:38:21,801 --> 00:38:23,431
to make tangsuyuk sauce.

1039
00:38:24,171 --> 00:38:25,231
And...

1040
00:38:25,841 --> 00:38:27,571
Korean tenderloin steak...

1041
00:38:28,501 --> 00:38:32,741
and chocolate pudding with whipped cream.

1042
00:38:32,981 --> 00:38:34,240
You know, something soft.

1043
00:38:34,241 --> 00:38:36,151
I came up with those.

1044
00:38:37,751 --> 00:38:39,181
I'm not sure if they'll like it, though.

1045
00:38:41,051 --> 00:38:42,750
I hope they like it.

1046
00:38:42,751 --> 00:38:44,320
(It's 10am, and they have 2 hours until lunchtime.)

1047
00:38:44,321 --> 00:38:47,490
- We should assist you, - Yes.

1048
00:38:47,491 --> 00:38:49,161
so tell us what to do.

1049
00:38:49,691 --> 00:38:52,430
- First, wash your hands.
-  Okay.

1050
00:38:52,431 --> 00:38:56,501
(Act 1, Division of Labor at the Mushroom House)

1051
00:38:57,301 --> 00:38:59,570
- We have to trim these, right?
-  Yes, we do.

1052
00:38:59,571 --> 00:39:00,841
- Okay.
-  Let's chop them.

1053
00:39:01,501 --> 00:39:04,211
Broccolini is already washed, but...

1054
00:39:04,541 --> 00:39:06,110
- Still...
-  Broccolini?

1055
00:39:06,111 --> 00:39:08,850
Broccolini. When it ends with "lini,"

1056
00:39:08,851 --> 00:39:10,210
it means it's small.

1057
00:39:10,211 --> 00:39:13,051
- Baby broccoli.
-  It's a different kind, though.

1058
00:39:13,421 --> 00:39:14,621
I've never seen that before.

1059
00:39:14,781 --> 00:39:16,890
Pick the small leaves.

1060
00:39:16,891 --> 00:39:17,920
Okay.

1061
00:39:17,921 --> 00:39:19,320
(Plucking off the small leaves)

1062
00:39:19,321 --> 00:39:21,291
Kind of like this.

1063
00:39:23,561 --> 00:39:25,930
(She trims it just like she was taught.)

1064
00:39:25,931 --> 00:39:28,660
- I saw firewood outside.
-  Yes.

1065
00:39:28,661 --> 00:39:30,730
It would be better if you could build a fire.

1066
00:39:30,731 --> 00:39:31,831
- The firewood?
-  Yes.

1067
00:39:32,301 --> 00:39:34,170
- Do you mean this?
-  Yes.

1068
00:39:34,171 --> 00:39:36,110
- This would make it better.
-  It would.

1069
00:39:36,111 --> 00:39:37,140
Yes.

1070
00:39:37,141 --> 00:39:39,340
- Should I start?
-  Yes, please.

1071
00:39:39,341 --> 00:39:41,680
- Okay. I'll start making it.
-  Okay.

1072
00:39:41,681 --> 00:39:43,551
- Please work on this.
-  Sure.

1073
00:39:45,451 --> 00:39:48,481
(Returning to the kitchen)

1074
00:39:49,791 --> 00:39:51,450
(He immediately checks the ingredients.)

1075
00:39:51,451 --> 00:39:52,561
Okay.

1076
00:39:53,291 --> 00:39:56,461
(Ripe persimmons)

1077
00:39:57,731 --> 00:39:58,961
With this ham...

1078
00:39:59,561 --> 00:40:00,561
Yes.

1079
00:40:01,331 --> 00:40:02,670
- Just like this.
-  Okay.

1080
00:40:02,671 --> 00:40:04,330
(Prepping the ingredients for deep-fried ham)

1081
00:40:04,331 --> 00:40:06,141
I want it to look...

1082
00:40:06,941 --> 00:40:08,840
like guobaorou.

1083
00:40:08,841 --> 00:40:11,511
I'm not going to fry small pieces.

1084
00:40:12,011 --> 00:40:14,340
- I'll cut them into 5 even pieces.
-  Yes, 5 pieces.

1085
00:40:14,341 --> 00:40:15,411
Okay.

1086
00:40:16,811 --> 00:40:18,480
The ham...

1087
00:40:18,481 --> 00:40:20,521
also contains eggs and ketchup,

1088
00:40:21,181 --> 00:40:23,290
so they'll go great with rice.

1089
00:40:23,291 --> 00:40:24,390
- That sounds nice.
-  Yes.

1090
00:40:24,391 --> 00:40:27,361
It's already well-balanced.

1091
00:40:27,921 --> 00:40:29,290
It's well-balanced.

1092
00:40:29,291 --> 00:40:31,191
- Right.
-  Yes, well-balanced ham.

1093
00:40:31,531 --> 00:40:32,701
It must be delicious.

1094
00:40:34,831 --> 00:40:35,930
This is perfect.

1095
00:40:35,931 --> 00:40:37,071
(At the fire pot)

1096
00:40:38,201 --> 00:40:40,541
The steaks will taste so good when cooked over this.

1097
00:40:41,601 --> 00:40:42,671
Kangnam!

1098
00:40:43,471 --> 00:40:44,970
You should check it out.

1099
00:40:44,971 --> 00:40:46,340
- Is it blazing?
-  Blazing.

1100
00:40:46,341 --> 00:40:47,410
All right.

1101
00:40:47,411 --> 00:40:49,480
If it's blazing,

1102
00:40:49,481 --> 00:40:52,480
we're going to use it in 30 to 40 minutes.

1103
00:40:52,481 --> 00:40:54,280
- It's going to turn into charcoal.
-  Yes, we're using charcoal.

1104
00:40:54,281 --> 00:40:55,850
We can add more firewood if we need more.

1105
00:40:55,851 --> 00:40:56,950
- I got it.
-  Yes.

1106
00:40:56,951 --> 00:40:58,021
(See you soon.)

1107
00:40:58,491 --> 00:40:59,990
Pour three bottles of milk, please.

1108
00:40:59,991 --> 00:41:02,021
(His next mission is to make dessert.)

1109
00:41:02,861 --> 00:41:04,790
- And boil it?
-  Yes.

1110
00:41:04,791 --> 00:41:05,960
(He pours 3 bottles of milk first.)

1111
00:41:05,961 --> 00:41:07,361
- For the color?
-  Yes.

1112
00:41:07,731 --> 00:41:10,471
(Adding cocoa powder)

1113
00:41:11,031 --> 00:41:13,541
Kids don't really like dark chocolate,

1114
00:41:14,371 --> 00:41:15,740
so I'm adding it...

1115
00:41:15,741 --> 00:41:17,671
to add a hint of sweet chocolate flavor.

1116
00:41:18,041 --> 00:41:20,441
- Do you have a whisk?
-  Whisker?

1117
00:41:20,981 --> 00:41:22,411
- Whisker?
-  A whisk.

1118
00:41:22,651 --> 00:41:24,650
I've heard of whiskey, but not a whisker.

1119
00:41:24,651 --> 00:41:25,680
The one you use to mix things?

1120
00:41:25,681 --> 00:41:26,820
- Whisker?
-  That's the one.

1121
00:41:26,821 --> 00:41:28,020
- Is this called a whisker?
-  A whisk.

1122
00:41:28,021 --> 00:41:30,151
There's a thin one and a thick one.

1123
00:41:31,551 --> 00:41:32,961
- The thick one.
-  Okay.

1124
00:41:33,391 --> 00:41:34,920
- Until it's solid enough...
-  It's harder...

1125
00:41:34,921 --> 00:41:36,030
because you have to tell us every little detail, isn't it?

1126
00:41:36,031 --> 00:41:37,991
No, I was thinking,

1127
00:41:38,161 --> 00:41:40,861
"You must have so many things to do here."

1128
00:41:41,061 --> 00:41:43,401
"I feel like I'm piling on with my cooking."

1129
00:41:43,671 --> 00:41:45,431
I thought you'd do everything, but we're doing all the work.

1130
00:41:46,541 --> 00:41:48,301
It isn't exactly the way I was expecting it to go.

1131
00:41:49,511 --> 00:41:50,870
- I should...
-  In my head,

1132
00:41:50,871 --> 00:41:52,640
my job ended with chopping those onions.

1133
00:41:52,641 --> 00:41:54,640
(There are more things to help him out with.)

1134
00:41:54,641 --> 00:41:56,410
It's going exactly as I planned,

1135
00:41:56,411 --> 00:41:57,611
- Really?
-  so I'm proud.

1136
00:41:59,481 --> 00:42:01,180
(Adding cocoa powder)

1137
00:42:01,181 --> 00:42:02,951
- It has to be sweet?
-  Yes.

1138
00:42:04,451 --> 00:42:06,890
If this doesn't make it sweet enough,

1139
00:42:06,891 --> 00:42:08,120
I'll have to add sugar...

1140
00:42:08,121 --> 00:42:09,761
- to finish it.
-  Okay.

1141
00:42:11,031 --> 00:42:12,301
This is... Okay.

1142
00:42:13,401 --> 00:42:14,401
Okay.

1143
00:42:14,402 --> 00:42:17,201
(The persimmons fall.)

1144
00:42:21,101 --> 00:42:22,270
Are you okay?

1145
00:42:22,271 --> 00:42:23,711
(The persimmons are crushed.)

1146
00:42:26,241 --> 00:42:28,481
(Flustered)

1147
00:42:31,651 --> 00:42:33,151
- Are you okay?
-  I'm okay.

1148
00:42:33,521 --> 00:42:34,721
Pretend you never saw it.

1149
00:42:36,451 --> 00:42:39,290
This makes it less sweet, right?

1150
00:42:39,291 --> 00:42:41,660
- Sorry?
-  Does that make it less sweet?

1151
00:42:41,661 --> 00:42:42,791
I think it'll be fine.

1152
00:42:42,861 --> 00:42:46,761
I think I miscalculated it.

1153
00:42:47,101 --> 00:42:48,230
I should have had tea...

1154
00:42:48,231 --> 00:42:50,131
after completely figuring out how the kitchen looks.

1155
00:42:50,831 --> 00:42:52,741
But I had tea as soon as I entered.

1156
00:42:54,001 --> 00:42:56,310
That was a bit of a crisis.

1157
00:42:56,311 --> 00:42:58,241
(Act 2, Whale Teacher's Crisis)

1158
00:42:58,811 --> 00:43:00,240
Where were you in the US?

1159
00:43:00,241 --> 00:43:02,410
I only stayed in California.

1160
00:43:02,411 --> 00:43:05,581
- California?
-  I served in the US Army.

1161
00:43:05,681 --> 00:43:07,620
- What? Really?
-  Yes.

1162
00:43:07,621 --> 00:43:09,390
- You were in the army?
-  Yes.

1163
00:43:09,391 --> 00:43:12,720
- What? No way!
-  When I was in the army,

1164
00:43:12,721 --> 00:43:15,990
I lived in the central and the eastern US.

1165
00:43:15,991 --> 00:43:17,690
- Really?
-  Yes.

1166
00:43:17,691 --> 00:43:20,430
After I got out, I started to cook.

1167
00:43:20,431 --> 00:43:22,531
- Did you start as a part-timer?
-  Yes, at first.

1168
00:43:23,101 --> 00:43:24,170
I had no idea.

1169
00:43:24,171 --> 00:43:28,970
- It was...
-  Again?

1170
00:43:28,971 --> 00:43:30,141
(Again?)

1171
00:43:30,541 --> 00:43:32,210
- We should put it somewhere else.
-  The persimmon...

1172
00:43:32,211 --> 00:43:33,211
Yes, we'd better move them.

1173
00:43:33,211 --> 00:43:34,211
This...

1174
00:43:34,211 --> 00:43:35,211
(The persimmons are being threatened.)

1175
00:43:37,751 --> 00:43:40,221
(Emergency evacuation)

1176
00:43:40,481 --> 00:43:41,880
- That looks good.
-  What?

1177
00:43:41,881 --> 00:43:43,050
The persimmon is very soft.

1178
00:43:43,051 --> 00:43:44,250
- Sir.
-  It's all ripe.

1179
00:43:44,251 --> 00:43:46,720
Hey, it's a taste every kid loves.

1180
00:43:46,721 --> 00:43:48,920
Exactly. That was what I was going for.

1181
00:43:48,921 --> 00:43:50,030
It's what kids love best.

1182
00:43:50,031 --> 00:43:51,260
It can't be helped.

1183
00:43:51,261 --> 00:43:53,400
If we have the taste down, add some starch.

1184
00:43:53,401 --> 00:43:56,900
We'll cook it with starch until it boils.

1185
00:43:56,901 --> 00:43:58,401
Then this will turn thick.

1186
00:43:58,971 --> 00:44:00,341
- We'll cool it after that.
-  Cool it.

1187
00:44:00,441 --> 00:44:03,071
Kids can easily eat it then. It's simple.

1188
00:44:04,311 --> 00:44:06,710
We'll go with our gut.

1189
00:44:06,711 --> 00:44:08,181
(Eyeing the amount of starch)

1190
00:44:09,611 --> 00:44:11,511
- I hope the ratio is right.
-  Exactly.

1191
00:44:13,181 --> 00:44:15,450
(Measuring with his eyes)

1192
00:44:15,451 --> 00:44:16,451
Okay.

1193
00:44:16,891 --> 00:44:18,190
(Sucking teeth)

1194
00:44:18,191 --> 00:44:20,021
This will turn hard once boiled, right?

1195
00:44:20,391 --> 00:44:21,821
It's sticking to the bottom.

1196
00:44:21,921 --> 00:44:25,460
When working on something with a lot of starch and sugar,

1197
00:44:25,461 --> 00:44:27,000
- you should scrape the bottom.
-  Scrape?

1198
00:44:27,001 --> 00:44:30,471
Yes, you can mix it while scraping the bottom.

1199
00:44:33,141 --> 00:44:34,171
I can't tell.

1200
00:44:36,171 --> 00:44:38,511
(Thinking)

1201
00:44:39,281 --> 00:44:43,651
- I don't know.
-  You don't know?

1202
00:44:43,951 --> 00:44:47,181
He says he doesn't know.

1203
00:44:48,181 --> 00:44:50,891
- You don't care anymore?
-  He doesn't know.

1204
00:44:52,091 --> 00:44:54,060
(What will be the fate of this "I don't know" pudding?)

1205
00:44:54,061 --> 00:44:55,061
Okay.

1206
00:44:56,061 --> 00:44:57,790
When do we cook the tenderloin?

1207
00:44:57,791 --> 00:44:58,961
- Tenderloin?
-  At the end?

1208
00:44:59,531 --> 00:45:02,330
It's 11:00am right now.

1209
00:45:02,331 --> 00:45:04,330
(It's currently 11:00am.)

1210
00:45:04,331 --> 00:45:06,070
- We'll cook it at 11:30am.
-  Okay.

1211
00:45:06,071 --> 00:45:07,271
We can start at 11:30am.

1212
00:45:07,971 --> 00:45:09,811
We need to time everything.

1213
00:45:10,941 --> 00:45:13,380
If you can wash that pot for me,

1214
00:45:13,381 --> 00:45:14,580
- Okay.
-  I'll make some pasta sauce.

1215
00:45:14,581 --> 00:45:15,711
- Okay, I got it.
-  Okay.

1216
00:45:16,081 --> 00:45:17,350
- I'm okay.
-  Are you okay?

1217
00:45:17,351 --> 00:45:18,911
(Cleaning the pot)

1218
00:45:19,951 --> 00:45:20,980
Olive oil.

1219
00:45:20,981 --> 00:45:22,150
(Pouring olive oil)

1220
00:45:22,151 --> 00:45:24,150
Put the garlic and onion in.

1221
00:45:24,151 --> 00:45:25,451
- Can I put them in directly?
-  Yes.

1222
00:45:26,461 --> 00:45:28,491
(Focused)

1223
00:45:29,591 --> 00:45:30,630
Is this good?

1224
00:45:30,631 --> 00:45:33,061
Yes. We need some gochujang.

1225
00:45:33,701 --> 00:45:35,700
Add a spoon and a half.

1226
00:45:35,701 --> 00:45:38,371
- A spoon and a half?
-  Yes.

1227
00:45:40,541 --> 00:45:43,210
Stir-fry it for about a minute before adding the tomato sauce.

1228
00:45:43,211 --> 00:45:44,271
- All of it?
-  Yes.

1229
00:45:44,471 --> 00:45:47,341
(Pouring tomato sauce)

1230
00:45:48,581 --> 00:45:50,380
- On low heat?
-  Low.

1231
00:45:50,381 --> 00:45:52,051
(Stir it on low heat, and it is finished.)

1232
00:45:56,091 --> 00:45:57,951
(Surprised)

1233
00:45:58,391 --> 00:45:59,461
It's really good.

1234
00:46:00,991 --> 00:46:02,631
- Does it taste okay?
-  It's good.

1235
00:46:03,391 --> 00:46:05,931
Really? Is this sauce good?

1236
00:46:06,861 --> 00:46:12,271
(A bee has appeared.)

1237
00:46:14,371 --> 00:46:15,871
Bee!

1238
00:46:17,711 --> 00:46:19,540
- We're very close to nature here.
-  Yes.

1239
00:46:19,541 --> 00:46:21,340
- Yes.
-  It's still beside you.

1240
00:46:21,341 --> 00:46:23,251
Where? It really is.

1241
00:46:23,351 --> 00:46:24,351
Come on.

1242
00:46:26,181 --> 00:46:28,020
- Chef.
-  Gosh.

1243
00:46:28,021 --> 00:46:29,080
What do we do with this bee?

1244
00:46:29,081 --> 00:46:30,550
- Once it goes away...
-  Bee.

1245
00:46:30,551 --> 00:46:33,291
It won't sting if you stay still.

1246
00:46:34,191 --> 00:46:36,191
- Don't move, and it won't sting.
-  It will burn if we don't move.

1247
00:46:36,531 --> 00:46:37,830
It won't sting if you stay still.

1248
00:46:37,831 --> 00:46:38,930
When can I do the dishes, then?

1249
00:46:38,931 --> 00:46:40,360
You must stay still.

1250
00:46:40,361 --> 00:46:42,000
(He must protect the pudding even if he's scared.)

1251
00:46:42,001 --> 00:46:43,700
Come on, Chef. Weren't you in the US Army?

1252
00:46:43,701 --> 00:46:45,970
- You were...
-  He was just joining me.

1253
00:46:45,971 --> 00:46:47,640
You crouched too much.

1254
00:46:47,641 --> 00:46:50,270
I thought you were going in the pot.

1255
00:46:50,271 --> 00:46:51,540
I was just joining them.

1256
00:46:51,541 --> 00:46:52,710
Your face is red.

1257
00:46:52,711 --> 00:46:53,741
Don't lie.

1258
00:46:56,481 --> 00:46:58,510
You startled me.

1259
00:46:58,511 --> 00:47:00,021
(He can be a bit sloppy.)

1260
00:47:00,821 --> 00:47:02,990
I think this is finished.

1261
00:47:02,991 --> 00:47:04,521
- Okay. Can you turn it off?
-  Okay.

1262
00:47:04,791 --> 00:47:07,261
It's going to be rose pasta, so I will add some cream later.

1263
00:47:07,861 --> 00:47:10,091
Now, do you see that pot there?

1264
00:47:10,291 --> 00:47:12,061
- "Pot?" - Take that pot...

1265
00:47:12,391 --> 00:47:13,530
- The biggest one?
-  Yes.

1266
00:47:13,531 --> 00:47:15,000
Fill it halfway with water...

1267
00:47:15,001 --> 00:47:16,171
- and put it on the stove.
-  What is a "pot?"

1268
00:47:16,271 --> 00:47:17,601
Now, do you see that pot there?

1269
00:47:17,701 --> 00:47:19,671
- "Pot?" - Take that pot...

1270
00:47:19,941 --> 00:47:21,040
- The biggest one?
-  Yes.

1271
00:47:21,041 --> 00:47:22,470
Fill it halfway with water...

1272
00:47:22,471 --> 00:47:23,570
- and put it on the stove.
-  What is a "pot?"

1273
00:47:23,571 --> 00:47:25,170
- What is a "pot?" - A pot. This one.

1274
00:47:25,171 --> 00:47:26,611
- A pot.
-  I see, a pot.

1275
00:47:26,711 --> 00:47:28,380
Do chefs call it that?

1276
00:47:28,381 --> 00:47:30,480
I'm just used to calling it that.

1277
00:47:30,481 --> 00:47:31,510
Is that a "pot"?

1278
00:47:31,511 --> 00:47:33,321
(English vocabulary: Pot)

1279
00:47:33,881 --> 00:47:35,051
How much water do you need?

1280
00:47:35,251 --> 00:47:36,650
- Fill it halfway.
-  Half?

1281
00:47:36,651 --> 00:47:39,121
Yes. It's the water for boiling pasta.

1282
00:47:39,861 --> 00:47:41,021
Will this come to a boil?

1283
00:47:42,191 --> 00:47:45,231
I planned this to be simple, but it's somehow hectic.

1284
00:47:48,261 --> 00:47:51,230
Sauce is done, and we're waiting for the water to boil.

1285
00:47:51,231 --> 00:47:52,470
We'll start cooking this.

1286
00:47:52,471 --> 00:47:53,601
(Now, the pasta sauce is done, and the pudding is being cooled.)

1287
00:47:55,001 --> 00:47:58,171
(News arrives from school.)

1288
00:47:59,681 --> 00:48:01,510
Really? Okay.

1289
00:48:01,511 --> 00:48:02,550
(The kids will be an hour late due to a swim lesson.)

1290
00:48:02,551 --> 00:48:04,550
We're going to eat at 1:00pm.

1291
00:48:04,551 --> 00:48:06,080
- What?
-  We'll eat at 1:00pm.

1292
00:48:06,081 --> 00:48:08,150
- Then, we have...
-  Not at 12:00pm?

1293
00:48:08,151 --> 00:48:09,390
- time.
-  We have extra time.

1294
00:48:09,391 --> 00:48:10,951
Let's do what we have to do first.

1295
00:48:11,051 --> 00:48:13,260
- Good thing we didn't boil pasta.
-  We can do it.

1296
00:48:13,261 --> 00:48:14,261
I'm glad.

1297
00:48:14,261 --> 00:48:15,261
(They can have a tasting session.)

1298
00:48:16,231 --> 00:48:17,231
(The ham they cut earlier)

1299
00:48:17,232 --> 00:48:18,791
The ham is out.

1300
00:48:19,861 --> 00:48:22,031
If you fry ham, what else would you need?

1301
00:48:22,361 --> 00:48:23,831
It will be the tastiest thing in the world.

1302
00:48:24,831 --> 00:48:27,271
I've never tried fried ham before.

1303
00:48:27,371 --> 00:48:29,001
Me neither.

1304
00:48:29,271 --> 00:48:32,341
I don't know. I just thought kids would like it.

1305
00:48:32,781 --> 00:48:34,411
It's guaranteed if it's fried ham.

1306
00:48:34,941 --> 00:48:36,710
How can it taste bad when it's fried ham?

1307
00:48:36,711 --> 00:48:37,881
It'll be tasty for sure.

1308
00:48:38,751 --> 00:48:40,120
Let's test it out and try it.

1309
00:48:40,121 --> 00:48:41,681
- I'd love to.
-  Yes. Let's try it.

1310
00:48:42,481 --> 00:48:44,890
If the kids are staying outside,

1311
00:48:44,891 --> 00:48:47,391
it might get soggy.

1312
00:48:47,661 --> 00:48:49,691
We have to make sure the batter remains crispy.

1313
00:48:50,191 --> 00:48:52,931
I don't know what time they will be able to eat it.

1314
00:48:53,301 --> 00:48:54,531
Doing a test is important.

1315
00:48:54,631 --> 00:48:56,200
There is so much. Gosh, it's so thick.

1316
00:48:56,201 --> 00:48:57,201
(Testing the ham tangsuyuk)

1317
00:48:57,201 --> 00:48:58,201
It looks tasty.

1318
00:48:58,701 --> 00:48:59,901
It looks tasty already.

1319
00:49:00,771 --> 00:49:02,041
(Plopping)

1320
00:49:02,441 --> 00:49:03,471
Okay.

1321
00:49:04,741 --> 00:49:05,741
What a nice sound.

1322
00:49:05,742 --> 00:49:07,781
(Always a tasty sound)

1323
00:49:08,811 --> 00:49:10,181
- It's floating up.
-  Yes.

1324
00:49:10,881 --> 00:49:12,151
It's a texture kids love.

1325
00:49:12,981 --> 00:49:14,351
This will be good for sure.

1326
00:49:19,561 --> 00:49:22,891
(Lethally tempting)

1327
00:49:25,531 --> 00:49:28,261
(The visual is great.)

1328
00:49:29,201 --> 00:49:31,231
- It looks okay.
-  I could eat two bowls of rice.

1329
00:49:33,701 --> 00:49:34,701
Is it crispy?

1330
00:49:35,401 --> 00:49:37,371
Gosh, it's so crispy.

1331
00:49:37,841 --> 00:49:39,310
What a crispy sound.

1332
00:49:39,311 --> 00:49:40,741
(Staring)

1333
00:49:43,551 --> 00:49:44,580
It looks so delicious.

1334
00:49:44,581 --> 00:49:46,450
(The crispy sound makes us salivate.)

1335
00:49:46,451 --> 00:49:47,621
Sauce. What about the sauce?

1336
00:49:47,721 --> 00:49:49,591
Sauce? I'll make it now.

1337
00:49:49,791 --> 00:49:51,490
- The persimmon...
-  Ripe persimmon.

1338
00:49:51,491 --> 00:49:54,090
We want just the meat of the persimmons.

1339
00:49:54,091 --> 00:49:56,061
- What happened to them?
-  They...

1340
00:49:56,361 --> 00:49:57,361
- That...
-  What happened to them?

1341
00:49:57,461 --> 00:49:58,561
We want just the meat.

1342
00:49:58,586 --> 00:50:00,356
- What happened to them?
-  They...

1343
00:50:00,761 --> 00:50:01,930
Sauce. What about the sauce?

1344
00:50:01,931 --> 00:50:03,831
Sauce? I'll make it now.

1345
00:50:04,031 --> 00:50:05,700
- The persimmon...
-  Ripe persimmon.

1346
00:50:05,701 --> 00:50:08,370
We want just the meat of the persimmons.

1347
00:50:08,371 --> 00:50:10,201
- What happened to them?
-  They...

1348
00:50:10,601 --> 00:50:11,701
- That...
-  What happened to them?

1349
00:50:11,801 --> 00:50:12,810
We want just the meat.

1350
00:50:12,811 --> 00:50:14,671
- What happened to them?
-  They...

1351
00:50:15,111 --> 00:50:16,910
- What happened to them?
-  Did the bee eat them?

1352
00:50:16,911 --> 00:50:18,641
They were new.

1353
00:50:19,681 --> 00:50:20,710
Are they too ripe?

1354
00:50:20,711 --> 00:50:22,921
They're... They look bad.

1355
00:50:23,781 --> 00:50:25,680
- Let's move on.
-  They look bad.

1356
00:50:25,681 --> 00:50:27,751
It looks like someone threw them.

1357
00:50:28,051 --> 00:50:29,621
This is too much.

1358
00:50:29,961 --> 00:50:32,020
But I think it's okay.

1359
00:50:32,021 --> 00:50:33,690
- Is this okay?
-  We can still use them.

1360
00:50:33,691 --> 00:50:35,031
- I'll just use it.
-  Does this look okay?

1361
00:50:35,531 --> 00:50:36,631
I'll try using them.

1362
00:50:36,731 --> 00:50:37,861
- Really?
-  Yes.

1363
00:50:38,261 --> 00:50:39,371
I respect you, Chef.

1364
00:50:40,571 --> 00:50:41,771
This doesn't feel right.

1365
00:50:42,401 --> 00:50:43,541
This one is really bad.

1366
00:50:43,941 --> 00:50:46,410
Let's put them in a bowl.

1367
00:50:46,411 --> 00:50:48,341
- Should I do it?
-  Yes. Let's use a bowl.

1368
00:50:48,641 --> 00:50:49,641
A bowl?

1369
00:50:51,211 --> 00:50:54,910
(Remove the calyx and cut the persimmon in half.)

1370
00:50:54,911 --> 00:50:55,951
It looks delicious.

1371
00:50:57,321 --> 00:50:58,951
- Do I peel it?
-  Remove the peel.

1372
00:50:59,451 --> 00:51:00,451
It's soft.

1373
00:51:00,452 --> 00:51:02,821
Yes. Remove the peel like this.

1374
00:51:04,521 --> 00:51:05,990
(Crispy fried ham)

1375
00:51:05,991 --> 00:51:07,661
I have to check the seasoning.

1376
00:51:09,201 --> 00:51:13,171
(Adding the sauce made out of just ripe persimmons)

1377
00:51:14,871 --> 00:51:17,701
(Whale Teacher is tasting it first.)

1378
00:51:18,971 --> 00:51:21,470
(I can hardly wait.)

1379
00:51:21,471 --> 00:51:22,481
Try some.

1380
00:51:23,011 --> 00:51:24,441
I think it needs some vinegar.

1381
00:51:24,681 --> 00:51:25,811
- Vinegar?
-  Yes.

1382
00:51:26,881 --> 00:51:29,751
(These two are having a taste.)

1383
00:51:31,381 --> 00:51:32,381
Gosh.

1384
00:51:34,091 --> 00:51:35,651
Gosh, the kids are going to love it.

1385
00:51:38,221 --> 00:51:39,560
They're going to love it.

1386
00:51:39,561 --> 00:51:40,561
They go well together.

1387
00:51:40,861 --> 00:51:42,631
- It's...
-  The combination works.

1388
00:51:42,731 --> 00:51:43,731
Yes.

1389
00:51:43,831 --> 00:51:45,401
- They go well together.
-  It's my first time trying.

1390
00:51:45,501 --> 00:51:47,330
Really? It goes well with persimmons.

1391
00:51:47,331 --> 00:51:48,770
I always...

1392
00:51:48,771 --> 00:51:50,840
It's good as it is. It's really delicious.

1393
00:51:50,841 --> 00:51:52,671
- Yes.
-  Do you need to add something?

1394
00:51:53,071 --> 00:51:55,141
The vinegar isn't for the sour taste.

1395
00:51:56,581 --> 00:51:58,441
- It's to heighten the taste.
-  I see.

1396
00:51:58,541 --> 00:52:00,411
That's why.

1397
00:52:00,451 --> 00:52:01,780
It just needs a drop.

1398
00:52:01,781 --> 00:52:03,150
(A drop of vinegar for a rich flavor)

1399
00:52:03,151 --> 00:52:04,251
Flavor.

1400
00:52:05,051 --> 00:52:06,421
- That's really little.
-  Yes.

1401
00:52:06,821 --> 00:52:07,890
It's so tasty.

1402
00:52:07,891 --> 00:52:08,891
(Will kids like ripe persimmons?)

1403
00:52:08,892 --> 00:52:10,020
We didn't do anything to it.

1404
00:52:10,021 --> 00:52:11,190
- No.
-  The taste of persimmons.

1405
00:52:11,191 --> 00:52:13,160
They'll go, "Is this tangsuyuk?"

1406
00:52:13,161 --> 00:52:14,231
- Yes.
-  Yes.

1407
00:52:15,431 --> 00:52:16,900
Good, the water is boiling.

1408
00:52:16,901 --> 00:52:18,901
(Meanwhile, the water came to a boil.)

1409
00:52:20,131 --> 00:52:22,670
This is Granobello Filini pasta.

1410
00:52:22,671 --> 00:52:25,070
It's from Italy and made out of farro.

1411
00:52:25,071 --> 00:52:28,140
This pasta is low in sugar,

1412
00:52:28,141 --> 00:52:30,380
but high in fiber and protein.

1413
00:52:30,381 --> 00:52:34,350
So people of every age group can enjoy it.

1414
00:52:34,351 --> 00:52:35,381
I see.

1415
00:52:35,481 --> 00:52:37,950
We should try using the timer and taste it.

1416
00:52:37,951 --> 00:52:39,290
- Should we use a timer?
-  Yes.

1417
00:52:39,291 --> 00:52:40,391
Timer.

1418
00:52:41,721 --> 00:52:43,160
- Should I start it?
-  Yes.

1419
00:52:43,161 --> 00:52:45,121
(Checking for the right duration to cook the pasta)

1420
00:52:47,291 --> 00:52:48,730
It has been 45 seconds.

1421
00:52:48,731 --> 00:52:50,401
(Adding salt)

1422
00:52:50,631 --> 00:52:52,871
- It's been 1 minute and 50 seconds.
-  Okay.

1423
00:52:54,401 --> 00:52:56,241
(Checking)

1424
00:52:56,301 --> 00:52:57,570
- Let's cook for 30 more seconds.
-  It's 2 minutes.

1425
00:52:57,571 --> 00:52:58,870
- Thirty more seconds.
-  Thirty.

1426
00:52:58,871 --> 00:53:00,211
We'll taste it together.

1427
00:53:00,811 --> 00:53:02,371
It's 2 minutes and 55 seconds.

1428
00:53:04,781 --> 00:53:06,611
Doing that makes me anxious.

1429
00:53:07,051 --> 00:53:08,711
We just passed three minutes.

1430
00:53:11,521 --> 00:53:12,721
We just passed three minutes.

1431
00:53:13,351 --> 00:53:16,391
(The look of a chef)

1432
00:53:17,591 --> 00:53:21,991
In 5, 4, 3, 2, 1.

1433
00:53:23,861 --> 00:53:25,631
We're now at four minutes.

1434
00:53:28,571 --> 00:53:30,371
I guess it's not hot to chefs.

1435
00:53:31,541 --> 00:53:34,041
- Grandmas are the same.
-  Yes.

1436
00:53:35,981 --> 00:53:38,040
Some grandmas grab grills with bare hands.

1437
00:53:38,041 --> 00:53:39,041
Exactly.

1438
00:53:39,042 --> 00:53:40,351
We're now at 4 minutes and 30 seconds.

1439
00:53:40,651 --> 00:53:42,151
I took it out at 4 minutes and 30 seconds.

1440
00:53:43,181 --> 00:53:44,780
(A chef's intuition)

1441
00:53:44,781 --> 00:53:46,021
At 4 minutes and 30 seconds.

1442
00:53:47,551 --> 00:53:49,191
Since I said I would make rose pasta,

1443
00:53:49,291 --> 00:53:52,260
could you pass me the sour cream over there?

1444
00:53:52,261 --> 00:53:53,331
That one?

1445
00:53:53,431 --> 00:53:54,660
- We won't be using this plate, - No.

1446
00:53:54,661 --> 00:53:56,000
but just imagine it.

1447
00:53:56,001 --> 00:53:57,900
(The tomato pasta will be the base.)

1448
00:53:57,901 --> 00:53:59,401
Okay. Serve it like this at first.

1449
00:54:01,331 --> 00:54:04,801
We'll put this on top for the kids to mix.

1450
00:54:05,801 --> 00:54:08,611
- Will it turn into rose pasta?
-  Yes, it will.

1451
00:54:09,381 --> 00:54:11,440
- Gosh.
-  It's different from what you know.

1452
00:54:11,441 --> 00:54:13,580
(After adding cream and cheese, a rose pasta is born.)

1453
00:54:13,581 --> 00:54:14,711
This too.

1454
00:54:15,011 --> 00:54:17,751
The kids can rip their basil leaves and put them in.

1455
00:54:18,151 --> 00:54:20,320
- Like so.
-  Basil smells so good.

1456
00:54:20,321 --> 00:54:23,020
It looks store-bought.

1457
00:54:23,021 --> 00:54:25,120
- Come on.
-  It looks like a restaurant dish.

1458
00:54:25,121 --> 00:54:26,790
I thought this would be okay.

1459
00:54:26,791 --> 00:54:28,091
It looks so pretty.

1460
00:54:29,401 --> 00:54:30,700
- Send it to me.
-  Okay.

1461
00:54:30,701 --> 00:54:32,061
It's so pretty.

1462
00:54:32,361 --> 00:54:34,271
- Should we taste it?
-  Yes.

1463
00:54:34,531 --> 00:54:36,441
This is how you turn it into a rose pasta.

1464
00:54:36,501 --> 00:54:39,070
- Just mix.
-  Mix?

1465
00:54:39,071 --> 00:54:40,341
- What is this?
-  Like so.

1466
00:54:40,371 --> 00:54:42,141
I haven't tried it either, but please go ahead.

1467
00:54:42,171 --> 00:54:44,381
- You should go first.
-  Should I?

1468
00:54:45,241 --> 00:54:47,250
We should think about...

1469
00:54:47,251 --> 00:54:49,250
whether we should give basil to them or not.

1470
00:54:49,251 --> 00:54:51,120
I think the kids will like it.

1471
00:54:51,121 --> 00:54:53,321
I think it will be unfamiliar to them.

1472
00:54:54,751 --> 00:54:58,520
(The basil's scent is strong, so people can be divided.)

1473
00:54:58,521 --> 00:55:01,061
Try it. I like basil in it,

1474
00:55:01,231 --> 00:55:02,461
but kids might not.

1475
00:55:05,701 --> 00:55:07,230
(This taste!)

1476
00:55:07,231 --> 00:55:08,231
Is it good?

1477
00:55:08,901 --> 00:55:10,271
This would be 30 dollars in Cheongdam-dong.

1478
00:55:11,871 --> 00:55:15,370
- It's so good.
-  In Cheongdam-dong? You're right.

1479
00:55:15,371 --> 00:55:16,681
It's so good!

1480
00:55:18,581 --> 00:55:19,651
Gosh!

1481
00:55:20,881 --> 00:55:21,950
It's so good.

1482
00:55:21,951 --> 00:55:22,951
(Delicious)

1483
00:55:23,521 --> 00:55:26,020
I think we could add less basil.

1484
00:55:26,021 --> 00:55:27,121
- Basil?
-  Yes.

1485
00:55:27,821 --> 00:55:31,361
- For us, it's better with basil.
-  Of course.

1486
00:55:31,461 --> 00:55:32,991
But I'm not sure about the kids.

1487
00:55:33,831 --> 00:55:35,491
But I think...

1488
00:55:35,791 --> 00:55:37,730
a new experience is good for them.

1489
00:55:37,731 --> 00:55:40,830
As a chef, it's important...

1490
00:55:40,831 --> 00:55:42,871
to let them experience a new taste.

1491
00:55:44,301 --> 00:55:46,270
It tastes more perfect with basil.

1492
00:55:46,271 --> 00:55:48,640
My kids don't eat a lot of basil either.

1493
00:55:48,641 --> 00:55:49,680
- No?
-  My son eats it,

1494
00:55:49,681 --> 00:55:50,741
but not my daughter.

1495
00:55:51,281 --> 00:55:53,611
I always debate taking it out.

1496
00:55:53,651 --> 00:55:54,810
In that sense...

1497
00:55:54,811 --> 00:55:57,550
Can't we put some on a plate and let them choose?

1498
00:55:57,551 --> 00:55:59,381
We shouldn't give them a choice.

1499
00:55:59,591 --> 00:56:00,791
There is no choice.

1500
00:56:01,091 --> 00:56:02,790
How cool. There is no other choice.

1501
00:56:02,791 --> 00:56:04,891
If they get to choose,

1502
00:56:05,021 --> 00:56:07,960
they'll avoid anything unfamiliar.

1503
00:56:07,961 --> 00:56:09,130
He's right.

1504
00:56:09,131 --> 00:56:11,130
- Let's try giving them some.
-  Sure.

1505
00:56:11,131 --> 00:56:13,131
- It's so good.
-  Let's serve it like this.

1506
00:56:13,471 --> 00:56:14,670
Let's settle it.

1507
00:56:14,671 --> 00:56:17,171
We'll now go outside.

1508
00:56:17,241 --> 00:56:18,440
Let's test the fire.

1509
00:56:18,441 --> 00:56:20,011
We need to cook broccolini in advance.

1510
00:56:20,571 --> 00:56:22,010
You have to cook it with scallion oil?

1511
00:56:22,011 --> 00:56:23,041
(They will grill the broccolini first.)

1512
00:56:25,281 --> 00:56:28,110
(The broccolini is covered in scallion oil and salt.)

1513
00:56:28,111 --> 00:56:29,351
When cooking vegetables,

1514
00:56:30,181 --> 00:56:33,820
I put them on high heat until they're about to burn.

1515
00:56:33,821 --> 00:56:34,950
Until they're about to burn.

1516
00:56:34,951 --> 00:56:36,421
Just before they burn.

1517
00:56:37,261 --> 00:56:40,160
I felt like we should have them eat some vegetables.

1518
00:56:40,161 --> 00:56:41,331
- Yes.
-  I wondered what would be good,

1519
00:56:41,891 --> 00:56:43,700
and figured something unfamiliar...

1520
00:56:43,701 --> 00:56:45,631
might be interesting to try.

1521
00:56:45,661 --> 00:56:47,901
I've never seen this vegetable either.

1522
00:56:48,401 --> 00:56:49,470
- Please grill it like this later.
-  Okay.

1523
00:56:49,471 --> 00:56:50,741
- Okay.
-  Okay.

1524
00:56:50,801 --> 00:56:53,040
We're almost ready, so go ahead and grill.

1525
00:56:53,041 --> 00:56:55,640
Once you're done, I'll come out to grill the meat together.

1526
00:56:55,641 --> 00:56:58,311
Cook the broccolini first.

1527
00:56:58,711 --> 00:57:00,951
I'll season this for you.

1528
00:57:01,111 --> 00:57:03,180
Will you come out when I'm working on this?

1529
00:57:03,181 --> 00:57:04,551
Yes, I'll come back soon.

1530
00:57:06,951 --> 00:57:08,791
We only have 30 minutes left. Will it be okay?

1531
